<h5>How do I specify dates?</h5>
 <table class="tips">
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find d 1997-11" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action16" value="Search" />
       </form>
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find da today and title neutrino&#42;" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action16A" value="Search" />
       </form>
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find da today - 2 and primarch hep-th" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action26A" value="Search" />
       </form>
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs">
      <p>All dates must be in the ISO format <br /> <b>yyyy(-mm(-dd))</b> <br />
      e.g. 2003, 2003-06, 2003-06-27 <br /><b>or</b> nov 1997, 18 nov 1997 <br />
      find d 199&#42; finds all papers from the 1990s.<br />
      Now, dates such as "today" "yesterday" "last month" and "this month" also work.
      </p>
      <p>There are also indexes for date-added (dadd) and date-updated (dupd) <br />
      find dadd &lt; 2010-10-03 <br />find dupd &gt; 1 oct 2010
      </p>
     </td>
   </tr>
 </table>
<h5>How do I find eprints?</h5>
 <table class="tips">
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find eprint arxiv:0711.2908 or arxiv:0705.4298 or eprint hep-ph/0504227" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action17" value="Search" />
       </form>
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs">
      <p>Note that the search term <b>eprint</b> is needed before "hep-ph/0504227".</p>
      <p>Eprint numbers of the form yymm.nnnn <b>must</b> be written as "arXiv:yymm.nnnn"; the old-style hep-ph/yymmnnn do not need "arxiv:".</p>
     </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find a unruh or t cauchy not t problem and primarch gr-qc" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action14" value="Search" />
       </form>
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs">
      <p>You can search on eprint type using primarch (primary archive, as opposed to cross-lists).</p>
     </td>
  </tr>
 </table>
<h5>How do I search by citation count?</h5>
 <table class="tips">
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
      <p>You can now search on any number for topcite</p>
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find a m albrow and j phys.rev.lett. and t quark&#42; and topcite 137+" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action" value="Search" />
       </form> 
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find a bando and topcite 100->500" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action" value="Search" />
       </form> 
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs">
      <p>Must be written in this format with no spaces</p>
      <p>Topcite searching is now general--any number of citations can be searched on.  You can also search a range such as 
      topcite 60->173</p>
     </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
      <p>Citation searching on individual articles can still be done.</p>
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find c Phys.Rev.Lett.,28,1421 or c arXiv:0711.4556" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action15" value="Search" />
       </form>
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs">
     </td>
   </tr>
 </table>
<h5>Calculating the h-index</h5>
 <table class="tips">
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input type="hidden" name="ln" value="en" />
         <input size="56" type="text" name="p" value="find af harvard u." />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action5" value="Search" />
       </form>
      <p>This will give you 
      <a href="/search?ln=en&amp;p=find+af+&quot;harvard+u.&quot;&amp;f=&amp;action_search=Search&amp;sf=&amp;so=d&amp;rm=&amp;rg=25&amp;sc=0&amp;of=hcs">
       this result</a>.<br />
      </p>
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs">
       You can perform any search and when it displays, then just choose the format <strong>HTML</strong> <strong>citesummary</strong> 
       from the list of available formats, and hit <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action9" value="Search" />
       again. The h-index will be displayed at the bottom. Unlike in SPIRES, there is no limit to the size of the search.
     </td>
   </tr>
 </table>
<h5>New Citation Operators: Articles Cited By Any Other Set of Articles</h5>
 <table class="tips">
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find citedby hep-th/9711200 and author cvetic" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action7" value="Search" />
       </form>
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs">
      <p>The articles by Cvetic cited in eprint hep-th/9711200</p>
     </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find a parke and citedby author witten" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action10" value="Search" />
       </form>
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs">
      <p>Parke papers cited by Witten</p>
     </td>
   </tr>
 </table>
<h5>New Citation operators: Articles that Refer To Any Other Set of Articles</h5>
 <table class="tips">
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find a witten and refersto author parke, s j" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action11" value="Search" />
       </form>
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs">
      <p>Witten papers citing author Parke, S.J.</p>
      <p>Note the difference between this example and the one immediately above it.</p>      
     </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find refersto hep-th/9711200 and t nucl&#42;" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action8" value="Search" />
       </form>
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs"> 
      <p>Papers citing hep-th/9711200 with nucl&#42; in the title (nuclear, nucleus, nucleon, ...)</p>
     </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find refersto a parke or refersto a lykken and a witten" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action13" value="Search" />
       </form>
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs">
      <p>Papers by Witten citing either Lykken or Parke (Boolean left-to-right, implied "and" before "author:witten")</p>
     </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="fin af oxford u. and refersto title muon&#42;" size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action12" value="Search" />
       </form>
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs">
      <p>Oxford papers citing papers with the string &quot;muon&quot; in the title</p>
     </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
      <p>Or the entire journal.</p>
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input name="p" type="text" value="find refersto j Phys.Rev.Lett." size="56" />
         <input class="formbutton" type="submit" name="action15" value="Search" />
       </form>
     </td>
     <td class="tips-rhs">
      <p>Find citations to an entire journal</p>
     </td>
   </tr>
 </table>
 <table class="tips">
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
      <p>
       N.B.:
      </p>
      <p>
       Be aware that the refersto operator finds the number of papers citing a given set of papers.  This is not the same as counting the total number of citations to those papers.  
       The refersto result includes papers citing multiple papers within the target set, and lists those only once. If you want the traditional count of total citations summed 
       over a set of papers, use the citesummary format, as described above.
      </p> 
     </td>
   
   
     <td class="tips-rhs">
     </td>
   </tr>
 </table>
<h5>Full-text Searching</h5>
 <table class="tips">
   <tr>
     <td class="tips-lhs">
       <form action="/search" method="get">
         <input type="hidden" name="ln" value="en" />
         <input size="56" type="text" name="p" value="find ft &quot;faster than light&quot;" />
